entry.title: Could Poland leave the European Union? | Inside Story

media:group.media:title: Could Poland leave the European Union? | Inside Story
media:group.media:description:
Poland is challenging one of the European Union's core principles. Regulations decided in Brussels are applied equally across its 27-member states, and override national legislation. But Poland's top court has ruled that parts of EU law aren't compatible with the nation's constitution. Other countries, including Hungary, have been at odds with the EU about the rule of law. So could Poland follow the UK and leave the bloc?
Presenter: Adrian Finighan
Guests:
Michal Wawrykiewicz - Co-founder, #FreeCourts Initiative.
Ulrich Brueckner - Professor of Political Science, Stanford University in Berlin.
Pieter Cleppe - Editor, BrusselsReport.EU.

entry.title: Burkina Faso opens trial on 1987 Sankara assassination

media:group.media:title: Burkina Faso opens trial on 1987 Sankara assassination
media:group.media:description:
A trial has begun in Burkina Faso for 14 people accused of involvement in the assassination of former President Thomas Sankara. Sankara came to power in 1983 and was shot dead four years later. He was a revolutionary leader who had called on African countries to default on unfair international debt. Among the suspects is former President Blaise Compaore. Compaore was deposed in 2014 following a popular uprising that brought an end to his 27-year rule. He lives in exile in neighbouring Ivory Coast and has refused to take part in the trial. His supporters see it as a political witch-hunt.
Al Jazeera’s Nicolas Haque reports.

media:group.media:title: Tunisia president approves new government
media:group.media:description:
Tunisia's President Kais Saied has approved a new government selected by Prime Minister Najla Bouden Romdhane. It has been a key demand of thousands of protesters who accused Saied of orchestrating a coup in July, when he dismissed the government and suspended parliament. These are live pictures of the swearing-in ceremony being held in Tunis. Among the new cabinet members is former banker Samir Said who will be the economy minister.

entry.title: Thailand expected to pass laws making torture, abduction illegal

media:group.media:title: Thailand expected to pass laws making torture, abduction illegal
media:group.media:description:
In a move viewed as long overdue by human rights groups, Thailand’s parliament is expected to pass laws making torture and abduction illegal. The issue has gained renewed attention recently after a senior police officer was caught on security camera footage appearing to torture a suspect who later died. Al Jazeera's Scott Heidler reports from Pattani, where there are many accusations of torture by the army.

media:group.media:title: Thousands rally against Tunisia’s President Saied

entry.title: Polls close in Iraq’s parliamentary election after ‘low turnout’

media:group.media:title: Polls close in Iraq’s parliamentary election after ‘low turnout’
media:group.media:description:
Polls closed on Sunday in Iraq’s parliamentary election with a low turnout after many people lost faith in the democratic system brought in by the United States-led invasion of 2003. The parliamentary election that drew one of the smallest turnouts on record, electoral officials indicated. It appeared to be the lowest turnout in any vote since 2003, according to election commission counts at polling stations.
Al Jazeera’s Ali Hashem reports from Baghdad, Iraq.
